00:28:08.152 --> 00:28:11.772
brand new Pelotonia, is the name of the event, Immunology Center.

491
00:28:12.612 --> 00:28:16.432
The reason why I bring that up is that a guy named John Byrd came to me, who

492
00:28:16.492 --> 00:28:19.292
was my head of hematology, and he said, "I need

493
00:28:19.312 --> 00:28:21.912
$100,000 to put this drug into mice.

494
00:28:21.992 --> 00:28:25.432
I think it's going to be a very interesting drug." That drug was ibrutinib,

495
00:28:26.432 --> 00:28:30.312
and John was the first one to put ibrutinib into a

496
00:28:30.372 --> 00:28:33.212
CLL mouse model. And many of you know the story of ibrutinib.

497
00:28:33.392 --> 00:28:37.152
Bill probably knows it best, much better than I do, but it's a multi-billion

498
00:28:37.212 --> 00:28:40.772
dollar drug and has literally changed the face of chronic

499
00:28:40.812 --> 00:28:44.432
lymphocytic leukemia. Anybody diagnosed with it now goes on it or one of

500
00:28:44.472 --> 00:28:48.312
the generational drugs that have since gone and

501
00:28:48.532 --> 00:28:49.172
can have

502
00:28:50.212 --> 00:28:52.891
normal or near normal life expectancy from that drug.

503
00:28:52.932 --> 00:28:56.632
So that started with $100,000 from a bike event

504
00:28:56.752 --> 00:28:57.892
and took off

505
00:28:59.572 --> 00:29:00.552
incredibly well.

506
00:29:01.692 --> 00:29:05.492
So those are things that kind of right within my wheelhouse that there

507
00:29:05.532 --> 00:29:08.622
was no problem with. And then the last one was that

508
00:29:09.772 --> 00:29:13.012
I was thinking, what is it that we have that the world needs?

509
00:29:13.452 --> 00:29:17.012
And one of the things everybody has, if you're an oncologist or you know

510
00:29:17.292 --> 00:29:19.622
family members with cancer, it's you don't know what to do.

511
00:29:20.152 --> 00:29:23.952
Somebody today, find out your uncle has cancer, calls you because you're in the

512
00:29:23.992 --> 00:29:24.352
field.

513
00:29:25.732 --> 00:29:29.712
Who do they see? What do they do? Is this an emergency? What are the next steps?

514
00:29:29.742 --> 00:29:33.652
And really doesn't know. So I was sitting with 120

515
00:29:33.712 --> 00:29:37.132
cancer physicians. Every one did one specific cancer.

516
00:29:38.152 --> 00:29:41.952
And the world was sitting there saying, "How do I talk to that person?" So I

517
00:29:42.072 --> 00:29:45.192
started a company, for-profit company, called Cancer Bridge,

518
00:29:46.392 --> 00:29:47.792
where basically,

519
00:29:48.692 --> 00:29:52.312
I went in partnership with someone who was doing the phone

520
00:29:52.432 --> 00:29:55.641
service for Apple Computers, Apple, the company,

521
00:29:56.452 --> 00:29:59.852
and he ran the telecommunications, and he was in Columbus.

522
00:30:00.502 --> 00:30:03.072
And I told him this idea. He happened to be a cancer survivor.

523
00:30:03.152 --> 00:30:05.972
He said, "I'll bankroll it." And it wasn't much.

524
00:30:06.332 --> 00:30:10.232
We basically used his infrastructure and started this system

525
00:30:10.352 --> 00:30:14.112
where we would go to a company and say, "How would you like it if your

526
00:30:14.152 --> 00:30:17.822
employee heard those three words, you have cancer, have

527
00:30:17.952 --> 00:30:20.832
someone to call who's an expert in that cancer?

528
00:30:20.842 --> 00:30:23.372
We're not trying to take your patient to our hospital.

529
00:30:23.392 --> 00:30:25.242
We're just trying to help your employees."

530
00:30:26.052 --> 00:30:30.012
Employers love this because they love their employees, and

531
00:30:30.032 --> 00:30:32.452
they want them to be safe and healthy and get the best.

532
00:30:32.492 --> 00:30:36.332
So this really took off, and within like a year, we had 100,000

533
00:30:36.392 --> 00:30:38.824
lives covered.I left

534
00:30:41.104 --> 00:30:44.824
after 21 years, Ohio State, and became the president at City of Hope.

535
00:30:45.344 --> 00:30:47.464
At City of Hope, I told them about this idea.

536
00:30:47.524 --> 00:30:50.804
They were thinking, "We'd like to do something." I said, "Oh, well, we have Cancer

537
00:30:50.904 --> 00:30:53.764
Bridge." So we went to Ohio State to buy

538
00:30:54.824 --> 00:30:55.944
Cancer Bridge from them, and

539
00:30:56.824 --> 00:31:00.764
we got all the way to the final signature, and the CFO refused

540
00:31:00.784 --> 00:31:04.524
to sign off on it. So we said, "Let's rebuild

541
00:31:04.604 --> 00:31:07.364
it." So we rebuilt something called Access Hope,

542
00:31:08.344 --> 00:31:08.724
and

543
00:31:10.004 --> 00:31:13.724
Access Hope, we got much more money behind it, much

544
00:31:13.784 --> 00:31:15.124
more entrepreneurial

545
00:31:16.304 --> 00:31:20.024
power behind it from our board. And we

546
00:31:20.104 --> 00:31:23.604
took that from covering 100,000 lives

547
00:31:23.684 --> 00:31:27.213
to at least six million lives right now.

548
00:31:27.284 --> 00:31:30.424
We have the Dana-Farber, Emory,

549
00:31:30.944 --> 00:31:34.184
Northwestern, UT Southwestern, and the Fred Hutch are all

550
00:31:34.244 --> 00:31:37.204
now share ownership of

551
00:31:37.924 --> 00:31:39.744
Access Hope. So

552
00:31:40.684 --> 00:31:44.034
these are both non-for-profit, Pelotonia, and

553
00:31:44.164 --> 00:31:44.924
for-profit,

554
00:31:45.924 --> 00:31:47.444
Cancer Bridge, Access Hope.

555
00:31:48.264 --> 00:31:52.144
And then lastly, Zomer said, "My lab is NK cells." I had

556
00:31:52.184 --> 00:31:55.944
someone come to me and said, "I'd love to fund your lab, but I want to

557
00:31:56.004 --> 00:31:56.524
make money."

558
00:31:56.984 --> 00:31:57.194
Mm-hmm.

559
00:31:57.704 --> 00:32:01.504
And I said, "Okay." So long story short,

560
00:32:01.644 --> 00:32:05.224
we co-founded a cell therapy company. You know this story with cell therapy.

561
00:32:06.644 --> 00:32:08.504
Maybe you don't, but it's had its ups and downs.

562
00:32:08.544 --> 00:32:10.754
Investors have been in, investors are out.

563
00:32:11.444 --> 00:32:12.784
We're now into in vivo,

564
00:32:13.964 --> 00:32:17.844
CAR T, CAR NK. So that's been a whole

565
00:32:17.884 --> 00:32:21.464
different experience, and at first it was within the

566
00:32:21.524 --> 00:32:22.364
organization,

567
00:32:23.324 --> 00:32:26.384
and then it moved out of the organization for a

568
00:32:26.504 --> 00:32:29.844
for-profit company. Had as many as 60 employees.

569
00:32:29.994 --> 00:32:33.844
Now has about a dozen employees. It's been up and down, tops and

570
00:32:33.884 --> 00:32:37.324
turvies, all sorts of things, but we're still plugging away and trying to keep it

571
00:32:37.384 --> 00:32:38.504
going. So

572
00:32:39.844 --> 00:32:40.844
it's been a fun ride.

573
00:32:41.824 --> 00:32:45.244
I've had the pleasure of working with wonderful people, the panelists that you see

574
00:32:45.304 --> 00:32:48.924
here. You need all of them, and so we'll stop there

575
00:32:49.084 --> 00:32:53.024
and open it up for questions, and if anyone has questions, come

576
00:32:53.064 --> 00:32:57.024
up to the microphone, and if you don't have questions, I'll start myself.

577
00:32:59.904 --> 00:33:00.264
Okay.

578
00:33:01.064 --> 00:33:01.464
So

579
00:33:02.344 --> 00:33:05.884
Omer, let me start with you because you talked about your

580
00:33:05.944 --> 00:33:09.864
pathway, but I think there are a couple of things that investigators

581
00:33:09.924 --> 00:33:13.784
need to know, many of which know. But what's a pre-IND?

582
00:33:13.824 --> 00:33:16.264
What does IND stand for? What's a pre-IND?

583
00:33:16.304 --> 00:33:19.604
What's an IND, and what's the difference?

584
00:33:19.664 --> 00:33:20.684
Sure. So,

585
00:33:22.404 --> 00:33:25.284
in the regulatory space, you have a product.

586
00:33:25.844 --> 00:33:29.024
You are ready to take it into clinical trials.

587
00:33:29.444 --> 00:33:33.084
What the FDA has code of federal regulations, and what it

588
00:33:33.104 --> 00:33:36.184
defines is something called an IND, which

589
00:33:37.124 --> 00:33:40.544
most of you have probably heard the term. It's an investigational new drug.

590
00:33:40.924 --> 00:33:44.544
So you have to go through an investigational new drug

591
00:33:44.724 --> 00:33:46.714
pathway, multiple phases of it,

592
00:33:47.564 --> 00:33:51.404
phase one, two, three, and then end up applying for a

593
00:33:51.444 --> 00:33:55.404
commercial license, and all these phases show different aspects

594
00:33:55.464 --> 00:33:57.124
of how the drug develops. So

595
00:33:57.944 --> 00:34:01.694
before the investigational new drug application is filed,

596
00:34:02.494 --> 00:34:06.444
the agency, the FDA, allows you to do something which is called

597
00:34:06.464 --> 00:34:10.304
a pre-IND, and actually, if you're in the cell therapy space,

598
00:34:10.364 --> 00:34:14.144
they also allow you to do with something called the pre-pre-IND, which is now

599
00:34:14.185 --> 00:34:18.044
called the interact meeting. But what a pre-IND basically is,

600
00:34:18.564 --> 00:34:22.393
is to take your baby, a young idea,

601
00:34:22.814 --> 00:34:26.584
and take it to the agency and have a discussion with them and

602
00:34:26.624 --> 00:34:29.004
discuss the development plan for it.

603
00:34:29.844 --> 00:34:32.824
What's the indication you're looking at?

604
00:34:32.884 --> 00:34:35.334
What's your outlook for how are you going to manufacture

605
00:34:36.444 --> 00:34:40.245
it? What dose are you going to use? What are the outcomes you're going to be

606
00:34:40.304 --> 00:34:42.104
looking at in the clinic? And

607
00:34:42.944 --> 00:34:46.644
at this very point, you will realize that the FDA is your

608
00:34:46.705 --> 00:34:50.544
partner in this, right? Not as a partner of your company, but as a

609
00:34:50.564 --> 00:34:54.265
partner in the development of the program because they will provide

610
00:34:54.324 --> 00:34:58.184
you very useful feedback at a pre-IND level

611
00:34:58.604 --> 00:35:02.564
and say, "If you take this into an IND

612
00:35:02.644 --> 00:35:03.824
for an application,

613
00:35:04.824 --> 00:35:08.524
this is likely to move forward appropriately," or, "You have

614
00:35:08.604 --> 00:35:12.264
major gaps right now in your program to have a first-in-human

615
00:35:12.324 --> 00:35:16.304
trial." So it gives you this little area where you can work

616
00:35:16.364 --> 00:35:19.924
on those gaps, so when you go in for your investigational new drug

617
00:35:20.004 --> 00:35:23.964
application to start a first-in-human trial, your chances

618
00:35:24.004 --> 00:35:27.994
of success are much higher. Now, I speak from a regulatory

619
00:35:28.084 --> 00:35:31.934
side, and I speak purely from regulations and getting that going,

620
00:35:32.004 --> 00:35:35.684
but I'm sure people who are trying to build a business model,

621
00:35:36.704 --> 00:35:40.324
if your IND goes in and the FDA says, "We're going to put it on a hold," which

622
00:35:40.344 --> 00:35:43.504
really just means right now that we see a safety issue here.

623
00:35:43.824 --> 00:35:45.544
We're not going to let it move forward.

624
00:35:45.964 --> 00:35:48.944
That's a big no-no from a business aspect of it, right?

625
00:35:49.084 --> 00:35:52.964
As a scientist, it's a hurdle. As a clinician, it's a hurdle.

626
00:35:53.004 --> 00:35:56.514
You try to fix that and move forward, but we don't know how long that's going to

627
00:35:56.514 --> 00:36:00.424
take. If the stock's going to drop, how is that going to

628
00:36:00.484 --> 00:36:04.264
work out? So a pre-IND becomes crucial in your development

629
00:36:04.304 --> 00:36:07.484
program if you want to take that product into clinical trials.

630
00:36:07.864 --> 00:36:09.664
So how do I get in touch with the FDA?

631
00:36:11.024 --> 00:36:11.364
Simple.

632
00:36:12.284 --> 00:36:15.264
There are very clean, laid-out procedures.

633
00:36:15.504 --> 00:36:18.944
Email is your world now. You can email FDA.

634
00:36:19.744 --> 00:36:23.704
On the FDA website, there's plenty of resources where you can just email

635
00:36:23.784 --> 00:36:27.104
them, call them, and they will provide you information how to

636
00:36:27.424 --> 00:36:30.124
officially apply for an application.

637
00:36:30.224 --> 00:36:33.724
So a pre-IND, it's a simple request you make,

638
00:36:34.504 --> 00:36:38.424
and there's very defined pathways on the timing.

639
00:36:38.604 --> 00:36:42.264
When you make a request, how long before the FDA responds to that,

640
00:36:42.844 --> 00:36:46.184
what you then need to provide them, and when they will give you your feedback.

641
00:36:46.504 --> 00:36:50.464
Now, there's no hard and fast rule when you need to

642
00:36:50.504 --> 00:36:54.414
go for a pre-IND. The FDA says, "Hey, come when you're

643
00:36:54.424 --> 00:36:58.004
ready to file your IND in about six to 12 months."

644
00:36:58.044 --> 00:36:59.924
So if you're going to file your IND

645
00:37:00.924 --> 00:37:04.424
early next year, it's probably a good time to have your pre-IND.

646
00:37:04.484 --> 00:37:08.298
And again-The one aspect, too, with

647
00:37:08.328 --> 00:37:12.028
everyone should remember, it's free. It does not cost you a penny.

648
00:37:12.088 --> 00:37:16.068
Well, it will cost you a penny internally to file it, but the FDA does not

649
00:37:16.128 --> 00:37:19.068
charge you anything. They will provide you this feedback

650
00:37:19.088 --> 00:37:22.258
completely free of charge using their experts.

651
00:37:22.648 --> 00:37:23.148
And so-

652
00:37:23.158 --> 00:37:26.588
So email it out, send it to them, send the application, and then you hear back from

653
00:37:26.648 --> 00:37:26.768
them.

654
00:37:27.088 --> 00:37:30.568
And when you do the IND, is that essentially your clinical protocol?

655
00:37:31.728 --> 00:37:33.708
It's a lot more than just the protocol, right?

656
00:37:33.978 --> 00:37:34.228
Okay. What is that?

657
00:37:34.648 --> 00:37:38.488
Yeah. So the IND is split into multiple parts, and at an

658
00:37:38.548 --> 00:37:42.388
early place, you have three extremely important aspects of

659
00:37:42.428 --> 00:37:44.588
it. The clinical protocol, absolutely.

660
00:37:44.648 --> 00:37:47.788
That's going to be your trial design, what your endpoints are going to be.

661
00:37:47.948 --> 00:37:49.628
How do you define success?

662
00:37:50.848 --> 00:37:54.788
I will tell you, in a Phase I IND, safety, safety, safety, right?

663
00:37:54.808 --> 00:37:54.988
The

664
00:37:56.168 --> 00:37:58.468
only thing the FDA cares about really is safety.

665
00:37:58.558 --> 00:38:02.328
You have to show your product is safe. Efficacy is going to come.

666
00:38:02.368 --> 00:38:04.868
You're going to find your dose. You're going to find an efficacious dose if it

667
00:38:04.908 --> 00:38:08.648
works appropriately. Safety. Number two is

668
00:38:09.008 --> 00:38:12.888
what they call CMC, which is chemistry, manufacturing, and controls, which is

669
00:38:12.908 --> 00:38:16.168
basically your process, how you make it. How do you make it in your lab?

670
00:38:16.248 --> 00:38:19.218
How do you make it in a manufacturing facility?

671
00:38:19.248 --> 00:38:22.258
What are the materials you use? What grade are they?

672
00:38:22.328 --> 00:38:25.328
How do you keep it sterile? All that stuff is going to go with that.

673
00:38:25.988 --> 00:38:29.928
And I went through it backwards. The number one thing, or

674
00:38:29.968 --> 00:38:32.888
the number three in this case, is your non-clinical.

675
00:38:33.288 --> 00:38:34.428
Those three are going to define it.

676
00:38:34.488 --> 00:38:38.268
So non-clinical is a key to getting an IND

677
00:38:38.328 --> 00:38:42.308
in. And what a non-clinical is, what in vitro, in

678
00:38:42.388 --> 00:38:45.648
vivo, animal model data do you have to

679
00:38:45.808 --> 00:38:49.348
show that this drug can be taken

680
00:38:49.428 --> 00:38:51.668
into a clinical trial into humans?

681
00:38:52.148 --> 00:38:55.688
If you have a drug that's making mice drop left and right in their model,

682
00:38:56.238 --> 00:38:59.628
it's not going forward. The Code of Federal Regulations

683
00:38:59.668 --> 00:39:03.008
requires you to have a safety study in there in animals.

684
00:39:03.108 --> 00:39:05.648
So it's hard to get away from that.

685
00:39:06.588 --> 00:39:10.528
The FDA is moving now to avoid using a lot of animal studies.

686
00:39:10.608 --> 00:39:12.508
They're saying there's enough data out there.

687
00:39:12.568 --> 00:39:16.368
There's extremely amazing tools out there where you can show with

688
00:39:16.388 --> 00:39:20.208
different ways, but you will have to run a safety study in animals first before you

689
00:39:20.228 --> 00:39:21.408
can take it into humans.

690
00:39:21.428 --> 00:39:23.458
And sometimes that's part of the pre-IND, right?

691
00:39:23.508 --> 00:39:24.108
Absolutely.

692
00:39:24.368 --> 00:39:24.608
Okay.

693
00:39:24.848 --> 00:39:28.828
Your pre-IND will have a big chunk of your in vivo, in

694
00:39:28.888 --> 00:39:32.848
vitro data, your basic idea how you're going to manufacture,

695
00:39:32.868 --> 00:39:36.808
and at least a synopsis of what your clinical trial design is

696
00:39:36.828 --> 00:39:39.388
going to be. You don't have to have everything nailed down.

697
00:39:39.668 --> 00:39:42.108
But you want to have enough in there

698
00:39:43.028 --> 00:39:46.748
for the agency to come back, give you some comments, and you incorporate that.

699
00:39:48.188 --> 00:39:51.648
For those who are right at the cusp of having a

700
00:39:51.668 --> 00:39:55.648
pre-IND meeting, and I will always say this as a regulatory person, as a person

701
00:39:55.668 --> 00:39:56.508
who worked for the FDA,

702
00:39:58.528 --> 00:40:02.308
you just want to hear "yes" from the FDA, because a lot of people want

703
00:40:02.368 --> 00:40:06.188
FDA to agree with their pre-IND. I can tell you 20 questions to ask where they will

704
00:40:06.228 --> 00:40:09.618
just say "yes." You can say, "Hey, we'll run a stability

705
00:40:09.708 --> 00:40:12.808
program." They'll say, "Yes, sure.

706
00:40:12.868 --> 00:40:16.748
That's right." But what you really want to ask is the on the

707
00:40:16.768 --> 00:40:20.718
border, on the fence questions, where you feel they may push back,

708
00:40:20.728 --> 00:40:24.528
but they may also give you very constructive feedback where you can take it all the

709
00:40:24.588 --> 00:40:28.148
way, right? If there's a model that's not perfectly defined

710
00:40:28.588 --> 00:40:32.388
and you think you're going to run an animal study on it, but you know it's really

711
00:40:32.428 --> 00:40:36.388
not going to answer the questions, propose to them and justify why you

712
00:40:36.408 --> 00:40:38.508
don't think that that study is necessary.

713
00:40:38.977 --> 00:40:40.968
And they may come back and say, "You know what?

714
00:40:41.648 --> 00:40:45.388
We'll look at your data that's already out there, and you don't have to run that

715
00:40:45.448 --> 00:40:49.128
study." And that study might be $200,000.

716
00:40:49.508 --> 00:40:51.868
So that's a good time to have that study discussion.

717
00:40:52.248 --> 00:40:52.808
Thank you, Omar.

718
00:40:53.268 --> 00:40:55.018
Can I ask a-- Can I add something, Mike-

719
00:40:55.018 --> 00:40:55.338
Yeah, please. Yeah

720
00:40:55.338 --> 00:40:56.868
... to that? Because I think that's so important.

721
00:40:58.868 --> 00:40:59.938
One piece of advice,

722
00:41:01.748 --> 00:41:04.208
no matter how much experience you or your company has,

723
00:41:05.048 --> 00:41:08.588
when the FDA gives you a piece of advice, you should follow it.

724
00:41:09.608 --> 00:41:12.108
If you don't, you're at your own peril.

725
00:41:13.028 --> 00:41:16.338
Remember, they have seen similar

726
00:41:17.388 --> 00:41:19.808
opportunities from multiple companies.

727
00:41:20.108 --> 00:41:23.348
So they already know often where the problems lie.

